body:
Verilator supports setting the name of the generated SystemC module using the --prefix option. This leads to compile errors when the prefix is the same as the verilog module, because a member pointer of the same name as the class is generated.

```
module myflop (input clk, r, d, output logic q);
  // dummy member for access
  logic [7:0] mem[7] /* verilator public */;
  always_ff @(posedge clk or posedge r)
    if (r)
      q <= 0;
    else
      q <= d;
endmodule
```

The generated code looks something like this when verilating using `verilator --sc --prefix myflop --pins-sc-uint myflop.v` 

```
...
SC_MODULE(myflop) {
  public:
    // CELLS
    // Public to allow access to /*verilator_public*/ items;
    // otherwise the application code can consider these internals.
    myflop_myflop* myflop;
...
```
This is illegal and will lead to C++ compile errors. Is there a way to rename the pointer `myflop_myflop* myflop`? Starting from Verilator 4.210 it seems that the pointer is always generated even when not using /*verilator_public*/.


Would you be willing to try to fix Verilator yourself with assistance?
Yes
